07557nam a22010335i 9783110639247DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020930897  a97831106392477 a10.1515/97831106392472doi  a(DE-B1597)507502  a(OCoLC)1153499193  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aZ105b.M4187 2020. 7aREL0400302bisacsh00aMaterial Aspects of Reading in Ancient and Medieval Cultures :bMateriality, Presence and Performance /ced. by Anna Krauß, Jonas Leipziger, Friederike Schücking-Jungblut. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 265 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMateriale Textkulturen ,x2198-6932 ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tMaterial Aspects of Reading and Material Text Cultures -- tMaterial Aspects of Rituals Beyond Their Instructions -- tScribal Production and Literacy at Qumran -- tScribal Habits and Scholarly Texts -- tReading Psalm and Prayer Manuscripts From Qumran -- tReading the Songs of the Sabbath Sacrifice -- tReading Material Features of Qumran Tefillin and Mezuzot -- tReading an Opisthograph at Qumran -- tCodices des Typs C und die Anfänge des Blätterns -- tAncient Jewish Greek Practices of Reading and Their Material Aspects -- tReading Early New Testament Manuscripts -- tWhat Ancient Christian Manuscripts Reveal About Reading (and About Non-Reading) -- tReading Regularly -- tEncountering the Grotesque -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndices0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThis publication seeks to endeavour the relationship between material artefacts and reading practices in ancient and medieval cultures.While the acts of reception of written artefacts in former times are irretrievably lost, some of the involved artefacts are preserved and might comprise hints to the ancient reading practices. In form of case studies, the contributions to this volume examine various forms of written artefacts as to their implications on modes of reading. Analyzing different Qumran scrolls, codices, Tefillin, Mezuzot, magical texts, tablets, bricks, and statues as well as meta-textual and iconographic aspects, the articles inquire the possibilities of how to correlate material aspects to assumed modes of reception and practices of reading. The contributions stem from Egyptology, Papyrology, Qumran Studies, Biblical Studies, Jewish Studies, Ancient Christianity, and Islamic Studies.In total, this volume contributes to the research on practices of reception in times past and demonstrates the potential hidden in text-bearing artefacts.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aHistory, Ancient. 0aManuscriptsxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 0aReadingxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 0aSacred booksxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 4aLesen. 4aMaterialität. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh  aMateriality.  aReading.1 aAskin, Lindsey A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohn, Yehudah B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Binyamin Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeilmann, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJördens, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrauß, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrauß, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.